{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/have-a-bot-haunt-your-slack-workspace-1aa333bb1873", "time": 1683007832.184861, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/have-a-bot-haunt-your-slack-workspace-1aa333bb1873/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Have a bot haunt your Slack workspace | by Adam Oudad | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Have a bot haunt your Slack workspace", "description": "In this article we\u2019ll see how to code your simple bot for Slack, and schedule it to run regularly. As some testing might be necessary, I recommend creating a dummy Slack workspace for this tutorial\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://slack.com", "anchor_text": "Slack", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://my.slack.com/services/new/incoming-webhook/", "anchor_text": "this URL", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://hooks.slack.com/services/SOME_GIBBERISH_CODE.", "anchor_text": "https://hooks.slack.com/services/SOME_GIBBERISH_CODE.", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://github.com/satoshi03/slack-python-webhook", "anchor_text": "slackweb", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.pythonanywhere.com/", "anchor_text": "PythonAnywhere", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://www.pythonanywhere.com/dashboard/", "anchor_text": "PythonAnywhere dashboard", "paragraph_index": 5}], "all_paragraphs": ["In this article we\u2019ll see how to code your simple bot for Slack, and schedule it to run regularly. As some testing might be necessary, I recommend creating a dummy Slack workspace for this tutorial.", "We first need to configure a web hook to communicate to our Slack workspace. Go to this URL, choose your channel and click on add a web hook. In this tutorial, I choose to post to the #random channel. The rest of the configuration can be left as is, so you can save it.", "Copy your web hook URL which should have the form https://hooks.slack.com/services/SOME_GIBBERISH_CODE.", "Let\u2019s test locally the connection to the web hook we just created. We\u2019ll use python library slackweb. The code is straightforward. We\u2019ll put this in slackbot.py.", "Replace the content of HOOK_URL by your hook URL copied from the previous step. Then run the code and check if it works; you should see in #random a message from your program. The first line of the above code specifies the location of the python interpreter to run, and the second line should be used if the file contains unicode characters, such as Japanese kanji or french \u00e9, \u00e0, etc.", "You could decide to schedule the program to run on your own computer, but if you want it to run even when your computer is shut down, we need a web server. PythonAnywhere offers free server space and python environment for development purpose. So let\u2019s create an account and head to our PythonAnywhere dashboard.", "Go to the Files tab and upload your file slackbot.py to your directory /home/your_username/.", "Then, let\u2019s install the dependency. Open a bash terminal and run pip3 install --user slackweb.", "Inside the same terminal, we can check that everything works. Run python3 slackbot.py, and see if the message appears again in #random channel.", "Scheduling is done in the Task tab. Create your task by specifying a frequency and the command to run: /home/adamoudad/slackbot.py. You can see the expiry date of your task when you created it, which is probably roughly one month. For the free plan, PythonAnywhere requests you to log at least once a month for your scheduled tasks to remain valid.", "That\u2019s it! You have your Slack bot up and running on the web. And it will haunt your Slack workspace until the end of times\u2026 cordially.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "(Machine) learning. PhD candidate at Keio University, Japan."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F1aa333bb1873&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_